comment: I run Manjaro on my laptop. It's a great distro. I think this situation could have been handled better, but the reaction to it was over the top and unwarranted. I take particular offense at people calling proprietary software "garbage". I have been a developer on and off for decades. I have written proprietary software for clients. I work hard to keep my skills current and to produce the best program possible. My work isn't "garbage" because I am paid for it, or because you can't examine my code (not that any of you do), and FOSS is not superior because it is free. When a bug turns up in a proprietary program, it has to be fixed, and it has to be fixed NOW. If a bug turns up in a FOSS program, oh well. Maybe you'll be lucky and it will be fixed in the next release. Or maybe the bug will remain unfixed for years despite repeated reports and requests from users. Try running a business that way. This "holier than thou" attitude is bullshit. I run MS Office in a Windows VM under Linux. I have certain documents set up to print a certain way. If I open those documents in Libre Office and print them, they do not look the same. The positioning is off. That's a problem. If this alternative office suite really works better than Libre Office for the things I need done, I will consider purchasing it, and I will be very appreciative to the Manjaro team for bringing it to my attention. If they get financial benefits from the arrangement, great. They deserve to be paid for their work, and begging for donations from people only goes so far.

When she talks about inequality, for example, I think it's always important to remeber the big historical picture of slavery, colonialism, imperialism, savage capitalism, institutional racism, etc, which enables us to understand the inequalities between countries, that is to say: "first-world" countries, the imperialists, exploring and marginalizing the rest of the world, creating social spaces deprived from resources, justice and autonomy, that is to say: social spaces where violence grows easily. Also, the way she addresses right wing and left wing politics, like they were both "partisanships" to overcome, sounds a little bit off in my opinion.. Just recognizing the devastating effects of inequality is enough to put this Talk on the left espectrum. It is the right, not the left, that defends the big corporations and elites responsible for maintaining such devastating inequalities. comment: Your point about beautiful math being engaging is one I've been making for YEARS. Every time we had a "problem solving" session in my ordinary drone of a high school math class, if the problem was interesting, challenging, aesthetic, and cool for its own sake, people were more engaged than any amount of the teacher telling us how useful the math we were learning would be for our careers. The students who would otherwise play on their phones or read books or otherwise zone out were actively offering insights, asking questions, and trying new creative ways to solve whatever puzzle was posed. To make math fun and engaging, it doesn't need to be useful for our careers and I don't quite understand why, when I tell people I study math, they ask what I'm going to use it for or why I find it interesting. No one asks that to artists, musicians, creative writing majors, etc. I'm really glad Grant is making this message spread farther than I ever could.

Later that evening and the next one, I tried to program the same function taking PNGs as inputs and definitions of the neurons and it honestly was only a little more rewarding.
